			<abstract>
				<p>We have attempted the crystal growth by the traveling-solvent floating-zone (TSFZ) method of La2−xBaxCuO4 with x ∼ 1/8, where the superconductivity is strongly suppressed. Under flowing O2-gas of a high pressure (4 bars), we have succeeded in growing single crystals of x = 0.11 with 5 mm in diameter and 20 mm in length. It has been found that both in-plane and out-of-plane electrical resistivities of the single-crystal La2−xBaxCuO4 with x = 0.11 exhibit a clear jump at ∼ 53 K. The temperature corresponds to the structural phase transition temperature between the orthorhombic mid-temperature (OMT) and tetragonal low-temperature (TLT) phases, T d2. It has also been found that both in-plane thermoelectric power and Hall coefficient drop rapidly at T d2 and decrease below T d2 with decreasing temperature. These results are quite similar to those observed in the single-crystal La1.6−xNd0.4SrxCuO4 with x ∼ 1/8, suggesting that the so-called static stripe order of holes and spins in the CuO2 plane is formed below T d2 in La2−xBaxCuO4 with x ∼ 1/8 as well as in La1.6−xNd0.4SrxCuO4 with x ∼ 1/8.</p>
